{
  "slug": "f1-is-a-fast-fierce-blockbuster-throwback-with-joseph-kosins",
  "title": "‘F1’ Is a Fast, Fierce Blockbuster Throwback, With Joseph Kosinski! Plus, The Future of James Bond.",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2025-06-27",
  "runtimeMin": 110,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins react to Denis Villeneuve landing James Bond and Aaron Sorkin writing and directing a 'Social Network' sequel, then review Apple's $300 million racing blockbuster 'F1.' Sean closes with an interview with director Joseph Kosinski.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The future of James Bond",
      "note": "Villeneuve takes the wheel; the odds on the next 007",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Arrival",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "Sean's favorite Villeneuve and, he argues, a masterpiece, adapted from Ted Chiang's short story and proof the director does his best work adapting other people's material."
        },
        {
          "title": "Enemy",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "'A movie that's important to me': the one with the spider, about living in Toronto and being divided as a man."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sicario",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "Cited as the ugly-in-the-shadows register the hosts would love a Villeneuve Bond to borrow, though they doubt Amazon will go that dark."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dune",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "Five or six years of Villeneuve's prime already spent on IP; a Bond adds a decade more. The hosts think he's great at it anyway."
        },
        {
          "title": "Blade Runner 2049",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "Part of the run that made Villeneuve the go-to big-tent filmmaker: the reason they call him an instant best-director-in-franchise-history the day he walks on set. He was announced without final cut, which is why Nolan (still at Universal on 'The Odyssey') was never realistic."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "'The Social Network Part 2' is happening",
      "note": "Sorkin writing and directing, no Fincher",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Social Network",
          "year": 2010,
          "note": "This podcast's foundational text: Sorkin and Fincher elevating each other at their peaks, a tightly focused character study. The hosts call it their generation's 'Citizen Kane.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Social Network Part 2",
          "note": "Announced sequel based on the Wall Street Journal's 2021 Facebook Files; Sorkin set to write and direct with no Fincher and no confirmed returning cast. Per Deadline it isn't a January 6 movie but spans the 2020 election, Facebook's effect on teens, and countries outside the U.S., which the hosts call fatally unfocused."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'F1'",
      "note": "Joseph Kosinski · Apple · in theaters",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "F1",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Kosinski directs Brad Pitt as Sonny Hayes, a late-50s ex-F1 driver pulled off the Daytona circuit to partner a hotshot rookie (Damson Idris) on Javier Bardem's last-place Apex team, which must win one race or be sold. Produced by Jerry Bruckheimer and Lewis Hamilton, written by Ehren Kruger, scored by Hans Zimmer, shot by Claudio Miranda with Carrie Condon as the team's tech director and Tobias Menzies as a board member quietly engineering the takeover. The panel loves it, a classical sports-underdog structure that shares Top Gun: Maverick's exact DNA, though they agree the racing is the reason to go and Pitt's dialogue scenes are the weak spot; he's best 'Steve McQueening' wordlessly. Loaded with dad-rock needle drops (Led Zeppelin, Queen) and staged inside real Grand Prix weekends, it's a massive act of Apple/F1 corporate synergy and, they think, the best motorsport movie ever made."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation with Joseph Kosinski",
      "note": "on making 'F1'",
      "guest": "Joseph Kosinski on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "F1",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Kosinski found the sport through 'Drive to Survive' and cold-emailed Lewis Hamilton, who gave him full Mercedes-garage access. With Sony he built a new camera rig (code name 'Carmen'), 16 mounts per car, wirelessly panned, because the Maverick cameras were too heavy. The strikes paused production six days in, letting him shoot 38 days of racing as second unit and rewrite a third-act wrinkle. Hamilton's note moved the endurance-racing opening up front (the original opening is now the last scene). Last great thing he watched: 'Tootsie,' on the flight home."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
